{{Spanish name|'''Tavárez'''|'''Mirabal'''}} {{Expand Spanish|Minou Tavárez Mirabal|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox officeholder |honorific-prefix = |name = Minerva Tavárez Mirabal |native_name = |native_name_lang = Minou |honorific-suffix = |image = Minou.jpg |imagesize = 180px |smallimage = <!--If this is specified, "image" should not be.--> |alt = |caption = |order = |office = Representative for [[Distrito Nacional|National District]]’s circumscription #1 |term_start = 16 August 2002 |term_end = 16 August 2016 |alongside = [[Alberto Atallah]] (from 2006 to 2016)<!--For two or more people serving in the same position from the same district. (e.g. United States Senators.)--> |majority = |succeeding = <!--For President-elect or equivalent--> |predecessor = |successor = ''incumbent'' |prior_term = |order2 = |office2 = Vice Foreign Minister |term_start2 = 16 August 1996 |term_end2 = 16 August 2000 |president2 = [[Leonel Fernández Reyna]] |vicepresident2 = [[Jaime David Fernández Mirabal]] |succeeding2 = |predecessor2 = |successor2 = |constituency2 =
|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1956|08|31}} |birth_place = Ojo de Agua |death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> |death_place = |restingplace = |restingplacecoordinates = |birthname = |citizenship = |nationality = Dominican |party = [[Alliance for Democracy (Dominican Republic)|Alliance for Democracy]] (2014–present)<ref>{{cite web|author=CDN 37|title=Juramentan a Cristina Lizardo y Abel Martinez|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0_EVEwSSKbw|accessdate=16 August 2014|date=16 August 2014|website=[[Youtube.com]]|language=Spanish|at=At near 1:55 min.}}</ref> |otherparty = [[Dominican Liberation’s Party]] (''circa'' 1995–2014) |spouse = |partner = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married--> |relations = |children = Camila Minerva & Manuel Aurelio |residence = [[Santo Domingo]] |alma_mater = * {{Flagicon|Spain}} Instituto Universitario de Investigación Ortega y Gasset * {{Flagicon|Cuba}} [[University of Havana]] |occupation = Politician, Professor |profession = [[Philologist]] |cabinet = |committees = |portfolio = |religion = |signature = |signature_alt = |website = |footnotes = |blank1 = |data1 = |blank2 = |data2 = |blank3 = |data3 = |blank4 = |data4 = |blank5 = |data5 = <!--Military service--> |nickname = |allegiance = |branch = |serviceyears = |rank = |unit = |commands = |battles = |awards = |military_blank1 = |military_data1 = |military_blank2 = |military_data2 = |military_blank3 = |military_data3 = |military_blank4 = |military_data4 = |military_blank5 = |military_data5 = }} '''Minerva Josefina Tavárez Mirabal''' (born 31 August 1956 in Ojo de Agua, [[Hermanas Mirabal Province]]), known by the [[hypocoristic]] '''Minou''', is a [[philologist]], professor and politician from the [[Dominican Republic]]. Mrs.&nbsp;Tavárez has served as deputy for the [[Distrito Nacional|National District]] in the [[Chamber of Deputies of the Dominican Republic|lower House]] since 2002; and served as deputy foreign minister from 1996 to 2000.
Tavárez was the presidential [[nominee]] of both the [[Alliance for Democracy (Dominican Republic)|Alliance for Democracy]] and [[Democratic Choice (Dominican Republic)|Democratic Choice]] parties for the [[Dominican Republic general election, 2016|2016 Dominican Republic general election]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Minou será candidata presidencial de Alianza por la Democracia y Opción Democrática|url=http://acento.com.do/2015/politica/8291672-minou-sera-candidata-presidencial-de-alianza-por-la-democracia-y-opcion-democratica/|accessdate=5 November 2015|publisher=Acento.com.do|date=15 October 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105215337/http://acento.com.do/2015/politica/8291672-minou-sera-candidata-presidencial-de-alianza-por-la-democracia-y-opcion-democratica/|archivedate=5 November 2015|location=Santo Domingo|language=Spanish}}</ref>
==Early life and family== Minou is daughter of Dominican lawyers and activists [[:es:Manuel Aurelio Tavárez|Manuel Aurelio Tavárez Justo]] and [[Mirabal Sisters|María Argentina Minerva Mirabal]], both founders in 1960 of the clandestine movement 14 June that sought the overthrow of dictator [[Rafael Trujillo]].<ref name=Ameco>{{cite web|last=Villegas López|first=Argelia|title=Minou Tavárez Mirabal: "Las hermanas Mirabal han legitimado la lucha de las mujeres universalmente"|url=http://www.amecopress.net/spip.php?article806|publisher=AmecoPress|accessdate=1 June 2013|language=Spanish|date=5 December 2007}}</ref> Her mother was assassinated by the dictatorship on 1960, and her father was murdered by the [[Triumvirate]] (three-member [[Military junta|junta]]) that overthrew [[Juan Bosch (politician)|Juan Bosch]]’s legitimate government in 1963, becoming an orphan at the age of 7 years. Her parents are considered as martyrs and national heroes.<ref name=Ameco/>
Tavárez is cousin and foster sister of [[Jaime David Fernández Mirabal]], a former vicepresident of the Dominican Republic.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}
===Ancestors=== {{ahnentafel |collapsed=yes |align=center |boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc; |boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9; |boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc; |boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc; |boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe; |boxstyle_6=background-color: #ffb; | 1= 1. '''Minerva Josefina Tavárez Mirabal''' (born 1956) | 2= 2. [[:es:Manolo Tavárez Justo|Manuel Aurelio Tavárez Justo]] (1931–1963) | 3= 3. [[Mirabal sisters|María Argentina Minerva Mirabal Reyes]] (1926-1960) | 4= 4. Manuel Tavárez Ramos (–1975) | 5= 5. Josefa Justo Rosseau | 6= 6. Enrique Mirabal Fernández (1895–1953) | 7= 7. Mercedes Reyes Camilo (1898–1981) | 8= 8. Aurelio Tavárez | 9= 9. Mercedes Ramos (–1841) |12=12. Simeón Mirabal Núñez |13=13. Adela Fernández |14=14. José Miguel Reyes Ovalle |15=15. María Camilo |18=18. Ponce de León |19=19. Catalina Ramos |24=24. Andrés Mirabal |25=25. Teresa Núñez |28=28. José Manuel Reyes |29=29. María Ovalles }}
==Career== She was Vice-Chancellor of the Dominican Republic for the period 1996-2000. She was elected Representative to the National Congress for the period 2002-2006, and re-elected in subsequent periods 2006-2010 and 2010-2016. She is President of the Committee on Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation of the House of Representatives, and member of several other committees.
