'''''Mother India''''' (1927) is a [[polemical]] book by American historian [[Katherine Mayo]] which attacks Indian society, religion and culture.{{sfn|Sinha|2006|p=248}}

==Content==
Written in opposition to the [[Indian independence movement|Indian demands for self-rule and independence]] from [[British Raj|British rule]], the book pointed to the treatment of [[women in India|India's women]], the [[Dalit|untouchables]], animals, dirt, and the character of its nationalistic politicians. A large part of the book dealt with the problems resulting from the [[child marriage in India|marriage of young girls]]. This was considered to be one of the main causes that led to an uproar across India after many newspapers declaring it scurrilous libel against [[Hindu]]s and [[Hinduism]].{{sfn|Field|1929|p=7}} Mayo singled out the allegedly rampant and fatally weakening sexuality of its males to be at the core of all problems, leading to masturbation, rape, homosexuality, prostitution, and venereal diseases.{{citation needed|date=December 2015}}

==Reception==
Mayo's book created outrage across India, and it was [[book burning|burned]] along with her effigy.{{sfn|Frick|2006}} Mayo's book ''Mother India'' was criticized by [[Mahatma Gandhi]] as a "report of a drain inspector sent out with the one purpose of opening and examining the drains of the country to be reported upon".{{sfn|Gandhi|2002|p=214}} The book prompted over fifty angry books and pamphlets to be published to highlight Mayo's errors and false perception of Indian society, which had become a powerful influence on the American people's view of India.{{sfn|Jayawardena|1995|p=99}}

Critics of Mayo accuse her works of being [[racist]], pro-[[imperialist]]<ref name="Teed">{{cite journal |author= Paul Teed |year= |title= Race Against Memory: Katherine Mayo, Jabez Sunderland, and Indian Independence|journal= American Studies|volume= 44|issue= 1-2|pages= 35–57|publisher= |jstor= 40643432}}</ref> and [[Indophobic]] tracts that "expressed all the dominant prejudices of [[British Raj|colonial society]]."{{sfn|Sinha|2006|p=68}}

In 1929, Harry H. Field, whom she had thanked in the foreword of her book wrote a book called ''After Mother India'' in which he responded to the criticisms made of the book, added more commentaries and wrote a brief biography of Katherine Mayo. A chapter was dedicated to the most important critique, that of Gandhi.{{sfn|Field|1929|p=3}}

After its publication [[Dalip Singh Saund]] (later a congressman) wrote ''My Mother India'' (''c.'' 1930) to counter Mayo's assertions.<ref>{{cite book|last=Saund|first=Dalip Singh|authorlink=Dalip Singh Saund|title=My Mother India|year=c. 1930|publisher=Pacific coast Khalsa Diwan society (Sikh temple)|location=Stockton, California|pages=218|oclc=3401226|lccn=30013748}} {{LCC|DS421 .S25}} {{OCLC|253315388}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Tisdale|first=Sara|title=Breaking Barriers: Congressman Dalip Singh Saund|url=http://www.pewforum.org/Breaking-Barriers-Congressman-Dalip-Singh-Saund.aspx|work=Pew Forum on Religion & Public Life|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|accessdate=March 10, 2012|date=December 19, 2008}}</ref> Another response to Mayo's book was [[Dhan Gopal Mukerji]]'s ''A Son of Mother India Answers'' (1928).<ref>{{cite book| author=Mukerji, Dhan Gopal |year=1928 |title=A Son of Mother India Answers |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=al3rIwAACAAJ&dq=editions:j0Q-czVT0s4C&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jH24VO_SOoOY8QW0jYHwCw&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA |publisher=E. P. Dutton & company, 1928 |accessdate=January 16, 2014}} Reprint 1928 by Rupa & Company, {{ISBN|978-81-7167-650-7}}</ref>

The title of [[Mehboob Khan]]'s 1957 Hindi epic film ''[[Mother India]]'' is a deliberate rebuke to Mayo's book.<ref>Sinha, Mrinalini (2006). ''Specters of Mother India: The Global Restructuring of an Empire''. Duke University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-8223-3795-9}}.</ref>

