{{sociology}}

'''Symbolic religiosity''' is a term coined by sociologist [[Herbert Gans]].<ref>[http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/01419870.1994.9993841 Symbolic ethnicity and symbolic religiosity: Towards a comparison of ethnic and religious acculturation HJ Gans - Ethnic and Racial Studies, 1994 - Taylor & Francis]</ref><ref>[http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&profile=ehost&scope=site&authtype=crawler&jrnl=0034673X&AN=10818446&h=TIa2n9UpZydn8O0kCwPea7H%2BiVItgKK9keBqQN2gwUKeQCauBw254QLqPsdORLwRWoSd904A2XYRI9Obn4DTQQ%3D%3D&crl=c Symbolic Ethnicity or Religion among Jews in the United States: a Test of Gansian Hypotheses. JA Winter - Review of Religious Research, 1996]</ref>

Gans explores the concept of symbolic religiosity as a concept parallel to, although separate from [[symbolic ethnicity]]. To Gans, symbolic religiosity is religious behavior detached from any comprehensive religious observance or religious affiliation.<ref>[https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF02965478 A critical commentary on gans'“symbolic ethnicity and symbolic religiosity” and other formulations of ethnicity and religion regarding American Jews S Sharot - Contemporary Jewry, 1997 - Springer]</ref>

